Connection between pulmonary artery and aorta","Opening in interventricular septum","Depression in left atrial septum","Opening between superior vena cava and right atrium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edepression in right atrial septum\u003C/strong\u003E, known as the fossa ovalis, is the remnant of the foramen ovale after its closure at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econnection between pulmonary artery and aorta\u003C/strong\u003E describes the ductus arteriosus, another fetal structure. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eopening in interventricular septum\u003C/strong\u003E would represent a ventricular septal defect. The \u003Cstrong\u003Edepression in left atrial septum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the fossa ovalis is visible only from the right side. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eopening between superior vena cava and right atrium\u003C/strong\u003E is a normal anatomical connection that is not related to fetal circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen ovale closes when left atrial pressure exceeds right atrial pressure after birth, as blood flow is redirected to the newly functioning lungs. The superior rim of the fossa ovalis is called the limbus, while the floor consists of the septum primum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinically, failure of the foramen ovale to close (patent foramen ovale) occurs in approximately 25% of adults. While usually asymptomatic, it can be associated with paradoxical embolism, where venous clots can pass directly into the arterial circulation, potentially causing stroke or systemic embolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The fossa ovalis is a depression in the right atrial septum marking the site of the embryonic foramen ovale","The foramen ovale allows oxygenated blood to bypass the fetal lungs by shunting from right to left atrium","The foramen ovale normally closes shortly after birth when left atrial pressure exceeds 